Sure, here's a simple example of how you can set up an S3 bucket using AWS CDK in TypeScript. This example will create a new S3 bucket with server-side encryption enabled, which is a good practice when storing sensitive data like customer financial records.

```typescript
import * as cdk from '@aws-cdk/core';
import * as s3 from '@aws-cdk/aws-s3';

export class MyStack extends cdk.Stack {
  constructor(scope: cdk.Construct, id: string, props?: cdk.StackProps) {
    super(scope, id, props);

    new s3.Bucket(this, 'MyBucket', {
      encryption: s3.BucketEncryption.S3_MANAGED, // Enable server-side encryption
      blockPublicAccess: s3.BlockPublicAccess.BLOCK_ALL, // Block public access
      versioned: true, // Enable versioning
    });
  }
}
```

This will create a new S3 bucket with the following properties:

- Server-side encryption is enabled using S3 managed keys.
- Public access to the bucket is blocked.
- Versioning is enabled, which means that all versions of an object (including all writes and deletes) are stored.

Please note that you should replace `'MyBucket'` with a unique ID for your bucket.

Also, remember that this is a basic setup. Depending on your specific requirements, you might need to configure additional properties. For example, you might want to set up lifecycle rules to automatically transition older versions of objects to cheaper storage classes or to delete them after a certain period of time.

Finally, remember to run `cdk deploy` to create the S3 bucket in your AWS account.

