Creating a simple login system in Python that remembers user sessions using cookies involves several steps. You will need to use a web framework like Flask, Django, or Pyramid. Here is an example using Flask:

```python
from flask import Flask, request, make_response, redirect

app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route('/')
def index():
    if not request.cookies.get('username'):
        return redirect('/login')
    return 'Welcome back, {}!'.format(request.cookies.get('username'))

@app.route('/login', methods=['GET', 'POST'])
def login():
    if request.method == 'POST':
        resp = make_response(redirect('/'))
        resp.set_cookie('username', request.form.get('username'))
        return resp
    return '''
        <form method="post">
            Username: <input type="text" name="username">
            <input type="submit" value="Login">
        </form>
    '''

if __name__ == "__main__":
    app.run(debug=True)
```

In this example, when a user visits the main page ('/'), the application checks if the 'username' cookie is set. If it is not, the user is redirected to the login page. On the login page, the user can enter their username and submit the form. When the form is submitted, the username is stored in a cookie and the user is redirected back to the main page.

Please note that this is a very basic example and does not include any form of password authentication or protection against Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) attacks. In a real-world application, you would need to implement these features to ensure the security of your users' data.

Also, storing sensitive information like username or password directly in cookies is not a good practice. In a real-world application, you would typically store a session ID in the cookie, and store the session data on the server, either in a database or in memory.

